\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 34. C. nudiflorus} Sm. in Sowerby,{\i  Engl. Bot.}{\b  7}: t. 491 (1798). Corm-tunic papery, with parallel fibres, the older tunics becoming fibrous; corm usually stoloniferous. Leaves 3-4, 2-4 mm wide, absent at and for long after anthesis. Flowers solitary, deep lilac-purple; throat white or lilac, glabrous or finely papillose-pubescent. Prophyll present. Bracteole absent; bract membranous, white, tinged with green at the apex, well-exserted from the cataphylls. Perianth-tube (5-)10-22(-29) cm, white, tinged with lilac or purple at the apex; segments 3-6 × 0·9-2 cm, elliptical to oblanceolate, obtuse. Filaments white. Anthers yellow. Style orange, equalling or exceeding the stamens, dissected into short, slender branches. Capsule c. 1·3 cm, ellipsoid; seeds brown, ellipsoid; strophiole indistinct. Flowering from September to October. 2n = 48.{\i  Meadows. • S.W. France, N., E. & C. Spain.} Ga Hs [Br].
\par

